ctionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym ap Meurig was born about 1332, in Breconshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Gwilym ap Meurig."},"et":{"about 1332–":"umbes 1332–Surnud","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1332":"1332","1354":"1354","about 1332":"umbes 1332","about 1354":"umbes 1354","1328":"1328","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of,Cantref Selyf,Breconshire,Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1332–":"noin 1332–Kuollut","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1354–Male":"1354–Kuollut","1332–Female":"1332–Kuollut","1332":"1332","1354":"1354","about 1332":"noin 1332","about 1354":"noin 1354","1328":"1328","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of,Cantref Selyf,Breconshire,Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1332–":"environ 1332–Décédée","1328–Male":"1328–Décédé","1354–Male":"1354–Décédé","1332–Female":"1332–Décédée","1332":"1332","1354":"1354","about 1332":"environ 1332","about 1354":"environ 1354","1328":"1328","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Galles","of,Cantref Selyf,Breconshire,Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym ap Meurig est née environ 1332, à Breconshire, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Gwilym ap Meurig."},"de":{"about 1332–":"um 1332–Verstorben","1328–Male":"1328–Verstorben","1354–Male":"1354–Verstorben","1332–Female":"1332–Verstorben","1332":"1332","1354":"1354","about 1332":"um 1332","about 1354":"um 1354","1328":"1328","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of,Cantref Selyf,Breconshire,Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym ap Meurig wurde um 1332 in Breconshire, Wales geboren. Sie hatte mit Gwilym ap Meurig mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1332–":"about 1332–Desede","1328–Male":"1328–Desede","1354–Male"